docs.text: with three movies already ( re ) released theatrically in america , and at least three more on their way , jackie chan is one of the newest " hot properties " in action adventure stardom , and it's just about time .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: for over twenty-five years , jackie's been starring in martial arts and action movies in hong kong , thrilling audiences with both an incredible grasp of acrobatics and martial arts and a wonderful sense of comedy .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: " drunken master " has the distinction of being the first jackie chan movie to " make it big " --this is the movie that supposedly set jackie up for big stardom in hong kong .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i'm not entirely sure why , exactly .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: in many ways , " drunken master " is similar to most of jackie's other early films , such as " fearless hyena " i and ii , " master with cracked fingers " , " half a loaf of kung fu " , " spiritual kung fu " , and others .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: in fact , looking at all these early films together , one gets the impression that they were stamped out , cookie-cutter style , at a rate of four to six per year , all using the same casts and telling very similar stories .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: to be honest , i think that early jackie chan movies are something of an acquired taste .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: they're quite different from action movies as we know them in america .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: these films tend to be set in the chinese countryside in an indeterminate period sometime in the distant past , with fairly slow plots that often meander far afield and sometimes seem to exist only for the intention of stringing comedy and fight scenes together .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: " drunken master " , though its plot is tighter than some , is no exception .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: ( as an aside , " drunken master " was the first jackie chan movie i ever saw , and i saw it the way it was meant to be seen . . . in
docs.label: positive

docs.text: a movie theater in seattle , as part of an asian film festival .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: at the time , i didn't really think it was anything special . . . but
docs.label: positive

docs.text: after having seen more films like it , it's kind of grown on me . )
docs.label: positive

docs.text: " drunken master " 's storyline is very similar to that of other early jackie chan movies , such as " fearless hyena " i and ii and " master with cracked fingers " --slacker martial arts student is taught the martial arts by a harsh-seeming master , and has a big fight with an evil bad guy in the end ( a formula that has been " adapted , " to put it kindly , by american films such as karate kid ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: more specifically , jackie chan plays the part of wong fei-hong , aka " naughty panther , " a fun-loving , practical-joking kung fu student who is too good at kung fu for his own good , but not _quite_ good enough .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: after embarrassing his instructor's assistant by beating him roundly , then beating up a bully in a marketplace , wong fei-hong tries to hit on a pretty girl , but discovers that she , and her mother , can hit back , better than he can . . . and
docs.label: positive

docs.text: is further chagrinned to discover that the two women are his cousin and aunt , respectively .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: his father , wong kei-ying , is unhappy about this , and is further annoyed when the father and brother of the bully show up to sue for damages .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: kei-ying soon institutes a harsh regimen of punishment , which fei-hong does not like at all .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: while escaping from this punishment , fei-hong meets up with a drunken old man , who proceeds to thrash him soundly , then take him on as a student and thrash him some more .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: this turns out to be su hua-chi , a legendary master of drunken-style kung fu .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: he assigns fei-hong a series of bizarre tasks , such as filling jugs with water while hanging upside down from a frame , cracking walnuts with his hands , and other such exercises , that seem like more pointless cruelty but are actually strengthening him up .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: then , when he's ready , he teaches him the seven styles of drunken kung fu .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: unfortunately , the lazy fei-hong only practices six of them . . .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: " drunken master " features some wonderful martial arts sequences , with jackie winning some fights and losing others .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it's been said before , but i'll say it again--these fights don't just _happen_ , they're as carefully choreographed as any ballet performance , and it shows .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: in his fights , jackie often makes use of objects found in his environment-- benches , jugs , cups , bowls , fruits and vegetables--often in new and surprising ways .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the fight scenes , particularly those toward the end of the film , are unparallelled in most american films .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: whether jackie wins or loses , it's really something to see . . . and
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it's often as funny as anything , too .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: and funny is the other thing jackie chan is very , very good at .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: there's very little that's new in this movie--jackie winning fights , jackie getting beaten badly by a master , jackie going through punishment or training . . . these
docs.label: positive

docs.text: schticks have all been seen before , in any one of several dozen similar jackie movies from the seventies and early eighties .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: but they're still hilarious as ever .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: likewise , jackie has a _great_ supporting cast , many of whom were also in other early jackie films , and they're often the source of plenty of hilarity on their own .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the really big thing about " drunken master " , though , that inspired several copycats ( including a couple starring jackie himself ) and a sequel fifteen years later , was the drunken-style kung fu .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i'm not certain whether or not this is actually a genuine style of kung fu , but the principle behind it is to imitate the wobbly movements of a drunkard to lull the enemy into a false sense of security . . . and
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it apparently helps if you're drunk while you're doing it .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: genuine or not , i have to admit , there's just something incredibly fun about watching a fellow who looks utterly sloshed wading into a group of startled opponents and making mincemeat out of them before they even realize what's going on .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: come to think of it , perhaps this element is what accounts for this film's success over any of the other jackie films . . . it's
docs.label: positive

docs.text: not just martial arts , it's the kind of martial arts that makes you stop and go , " whoa . . . "
docs.label: positive

docs.text: on the negative side , the cinematography in this film is nothing special , the film stock is rather primitive , the plot is often rather slow , and the subtitles are sometimes extremely hard to read against the background .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: " gone with the wind " , this isn't .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: still , if you like martial arts films , or like what you've seen so far of jackie chan and want to see more , give it a shot .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it's much more " real " than chuck norris or jean-claude van damme .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: another interesting thing about " drunken master " has to do with its video availability in the us .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: " drunken master " is the only early jackie chan movie that i know of that you can find in its original , letterboxed , hong kong subtitled form , commercially available on vhs ( from magnum video , in a gold box , for about $10 ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: there are plenty of other early jackie films around , but these are typically either in dubbed , pan-and-scanned form or else import tapes priced for rental instead of purchase .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: thankfully , " drunken master " , at least , is available in the aspect ratio in which it was meant to be seen , at a very affordable price .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: if you like " drunken master " , take a look at the numerous other early jackie chan films that are out there ( even the dubbed ones aren't really _too_ bad . . . if
docs.label: positive

docs.text: nothing else , you can enjoy the martial arts choreography while making fun of the dialogue ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i particularly recommend " spiritual kung fu " , " half a loaf of kung fu " , the " fearless hyena " movies , and " snake & crane arts of shaolin " .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: also , the mostly-unrelated-storywise sequel , " drunken master ii " , will hit theaters in american release sometime later this year ( though what its american-release title will be is still uncertain ) and comes _highly_ recommended by this reviewer .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: also , for a rather different interpretation of the character wong fei-hong ( who is in fact a popular figure from chinese folklore ) , i've been told to suggest the " once upon a time in china " series starring jet li ( though i haven't personally seen any of them yet ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: if you choose to watch " drunken master " , i really hope you enjoy it , and i hope it starts to open your eyes to the wonderful world of asian cinema that's out there .
docs.label: positive
